<details>
  <summary>Note about Windows command escaping</summary>

This document will use Linux/MacOS RPC syntax. When running rpc commands on Windows, you'll need to escape all quotes with backslashes.

For example, here is a typical RPC command on Linux and MacOS:

```powershell
chia rpc wallet create_new_wallet '{"wallet_type": "nft_wallet"}'
```

To run the same command on Windows, you need to escape the quotes, so it looks like this:
```powershell  
chia rpc wallet create_new_wallet '{\"wallet_type\": \"nft_wallet\"}'
```
</details>

## Reference

### `nft_mint_nft`

Functionality: Mint a new NFT

Usage: chia rpc wallet [OPTIONS] nft_mint_nft [REQUEST]

Options:

| Short Command | Long Command | Type | Required | Description                                                         |
| :------------ | :----------- | :--- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| -j            | --json-file  | TEXT | False    | Instead of REQUEST, provide a json file containing the request data |
| -h            | --help       | None | False    | Show a help message and exit                                        |

Request Parameters:

| Parameter          | Required | Description                                                                                                                                                                                       |
| :----------------- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| wallet_id          | True     | The Wallet ID in which to mint an NFT                                                                                                                                                             |
| uris               | True     | A list of URIs to mark the location(s) of the NFT                                                                                                                                                 |
| hash               | True     | The hash of the NFT's data. This should use sha256 for proper verification against the URI list                                                                                                   |
| did_id             | False    | Optionally specify the DID to be associated with this NFT                                                                                                                                         |
| meta_uris          | False    | A list of URIs to mark the location(s) of the NFT's metadata                                                                                                                                      |
| meta_hash          | False    | The hash of the NFT's metadata                                                                                                                                                                    |
| license_uris       | False    | A list of URIs to mark the location(s) of the NFT's license                                                                                                                                       |
| license_hash       | False    | The hash of the NFT's license                                                                                                                                                                     |
| royalty_address    | False    | The wallet address of the NFT's artist. This is where royalties will be sent. It could be either an XCH address or a DID address                                                                  |
| royalty_percentage | False    | The royalty that will go to the original artist each time the NFT is sold. The percentage is multiplied by 100 -- for example, to set a 3% royalty, set this value to 300. The default value is 0 |
| target_address     | False    | The wallet address of the initial owner of the NFT. This may be the same as the royalty address                                                                                                   |
| fee                | False    | The one-time blockchain fee to be used upon minting the NFT                                                                                                                                       |
| series_number [(WARNING)](#editions-and-series) | False    | If this NFT has multiple **editions** (multiple identical copies of an NFT), then this parameter indicates the edition number of this NFT.                                                                                                |
| series_total [(WARNING)](#editions-and-series) | False    | If this NFT has multiple **editions**, then this parameter indicates the total number of editions of this NFT. This parameter should be used if and only if the `series_number` parameter was also used                                                                                                       |

:::danger Warning
#### Editions and Series
v1.4.0 of the Chia client uses the terms *editions* and *series* inconsistently. It's important to understand the meaning before using these flags.

***Editions*** of an NFT refer to multiple identical copies of the same data (usually an image). For example, if an NFT is edition 1 of 5, this means there will be 5 NFTs with the same identical data, and this is the first.

***Series*** of an NFT refers to a sequence or ordering of unique NFTs (i.e. not identical copies). Often the entirety of a collection will be a single sequence. For example, the first NFT in a collection of 100 NFTs will be series number 1 of 100; the second NFT will be series number 2 of 100; etc.

In Chia, the **edition** of an NFT is stored on chain, but in v1.4.0 of the Chia client, this was mistakenly referred to as the series in several places. In v1.4.1, this will be rectified and made consistent throughout the RPCs, CLI and GUI.

If you are using v1.4.0, you can continue to use the `series_number` and `series_total` parameters, but be aware that these refer to the **edition number** and **edition total number** respectively.

To attach a series number to your NFT, you can include this information in the off-chain metadata file. This could be done through a custom field for the series, or a common practice is to include the series number in the NFT name e.g. *Chia Friends #1*, *Chia Friends #2*, etc.
:::

### `nft_get_nfts`

Functionality: Show all NFTs in a given wallet

Usage: chia rpc wallet [OPTIONS] nft_get_nfts [REQUEST]

Options:

| Short Command | Long Command | Type | Required | Description                                                         |
| :------------ | :----------- | :--- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| -j            | --json-file  | TEXT | False    | Instead of REQUEST, provide a json file containing the request data |
| -h            | --help       | None | False    | Show a help message and exit                                        |

Request Parameters:

| Parameter | Required | Description                                   |
| :-------- | :------- | :-------------------------------------------- |
| wallet_id | True     | The Wallet ID from which to retrieve the NFTs |

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

```json
chia rpc wallet nft_get_nfts '{"wallet_id": 2}'
```

### `nft_transfer_nft`

Functionality: Transfer an NFT to a new wallet address

Usage: chia rpc wallet [OPTIONS] nft_transfer_nft [REQUEST]

Options:

| Short Command | Long Command | Type | Required | Description                                                         |
| :------------ | :----------- | :--- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| -j            | --json-file  | TEXT | False    | Instead of REQUEST, provide a json file containing the request data |
| -h            | --help       | None | False    | Show a help message and exit                                        |

Request Parameters:

| Parameter      | Required | Description                                                                                                         |
| :------------- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| wallet_id      | True     | The Wallet ID of the NFT to transfer                                                                                |
| target_address | True     | The address to transfer the NFT to. For NFT0 this must be an XCH address. For NFT1 this could also be a DID address |
| nft_coin_id    | True     | The coin ID of the NFT to transfer                                                                                  |
| fee            | False    | The one-time blockchain fee to be used upon transferring the NFT                                                    |

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

```json
chia rpc wallet nft_transfer_nft '
{
    "wallet_id": 2,

    "nft_coin_id": "0x2691a4aa3533a3b3ef57cc8f70af22f1238d8961fb6b98b4f48eb34b61dc47b1",
    "fee": 10000000
}'
```

### `nft_get_info`

Functionality: Get info about an NFT

Usage: chia rpc wallet [OPTIONS] nft_get_info [REQUEST]

Options:

| Short Command | Long Command | Type | Required | Description                                                         |
| :------------ | :----------- | :--- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| -j            | --json-file  | TEXT | False    | Instead of REQUEST, provide a json file containing the request data |
| -h            | --help       | None | False    | Show a help message and exit                                        |

Request Parameters:

| Parameter | Required | Description                                          |
| :-------- | :------- | :--------------------------------------------------- |
| wallet_id | True     | The Wallet ID of the NFT from which to retrieve info |
| coin_id   | True     | The coin ID of the NFT about which to retrieve info  |

:::info
`coin_id` can refer to the specific `nft_coin_id` pertaining to this NFT, or to the `launcher_id`, or to the bech32m encoded launcher id
:::

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

```json
chia rpc wallet nft_get_info '{

}'
```

### `nft_add_uri`

Functionality: Add a new URI to the location URI list

Usage: chia rpc wallet [OPTIONS] nft_add_uri [REQUEST]

Options:

| Short Command | Long Command | Type | Required | Description                                                         |
| :------------ | :----------- | :--- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| -j            | --json-file  | TEXT | False    | Instead of REQUEST, provide a json file containing the request data |
| -h            | --help       | None | False    | Show a help message and exit                                        |

Request Parameters:

| Parameter   | Required | Description                                                               |
| :---------- | :------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| wallet_id   | True     | The Wallet ID of the DID wallet to transfer                               |
| nft_coin_id | True     | The coin ID of the NFT on which to add a URI                              |
| key         | True     | Must be either `u` (data URI), `mu` (metadata URI), or `lu` (license URI) |
| uri         | True     | The URI to add                                                            |

:::info

- You can only update one type of key in one spend, and you can only add a single URI per spend
- The new URI will be prepended to the existing list
- If the new URI is inaccessible, some wallets may not continue to traverse the URI list

<details>
<summary>Example</summary>

